      <hedline>
        <hl1>Shock Waves From the Mideast, on Two Fronts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Brian D Hanley letter says Yasir Arafat is pawn in larger game involving Israel, US and entire Arab world (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While absorbing William Safire's Oct. 12 column about the Middle East tragedy, I couldn't help but feel that the focus of his blame was misdirected. Yasir Arafat is but a pawn in a larger game involving Israel, the United States and the entire Arab world.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While absorbing William Safire's Oct. 12 column about the Middle East tragedy, I couldn't help but feel that the focus of his blame was misdirected. Yasir Arafat is but a pawn in a larger game involving Israel, the United States and the entire Arab world.</p>
        <p>Simply put, the violence in Israel must cease. Laying blame serves no purpose other than to continue on the path of divisiveness. An ethos of healing must reveal itself, perhaps resembling the truth and reconciliation processes in South Africa and Guatemala. Until perpetrators, victims and survivors on both sides are respected and heard, there can be no just peace.</p>
        <p>BRIAN D. HANLEY  New York, Oct. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
